'''Trevor Noah''' (born 20 February 1984) is a [[South African]] comedian, TV and radio host, and actor.<ref name="thedailybeast1">{{cite web |author=Jesse Lichtenstein |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/06/17/can-trevor-noah-s-comedy-jump-from-south-africa-to-the-u-s.html |title=Can Trevor Noah's comedy jump from South Africa to the U.S.? |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=18 June 2012 |accessdate=4 November 2012 }}</ref> In March 2015, [[Comedy Central]] announced that Noah would become the host of ''[[The Daily Show]]'', following the departure of [[Jon Stewart]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-32114257 |title=Trevor Noah to replace Jon Stewart on The Daily Show] |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=30 March 2015|accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref>

==Early life and family==
Noah was born in Johannesburg, South Africa. His mother, Patricia Nombuyiselo Noah,<!--Her full name (as it appears in legal documents) is Patricia Nombuyiselo Noah. News and media refer to her as both "Patricia Noah" or "Nombuyiselo Noah" or her full name.--> is black South African ([[Xhosa people|Xhosa]]), and his father Robert is a white native of Switzerland.<ref name="nytimes33114">{{cite news|authorlink=Dave Itzkoff|last1=Itzkoff|first1=Dave|title=Trevor Noah to Succeed Jon Stewart on ‘The Daily Show’|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/31/arts/television/trevor-noah-to-succeed-jon-stewart-on-the-daily-show.html?_r=1|accessdate=11 April 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=31 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="Armstrong">{{cite news |author=Stephen Armstrong |title=Heard the one about the Swiss South African? |publisher=''[[Sunday Times]]'' ''Culture'' magazine |date=16 December 2012 |pages=12–13 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/whats-on/comedy-gigs/south-african-comedian-trevor-noah-6319931|title=South African comedian Trevor Noah to play Birmingham’s Glee Club|author=Roz Laws|date=22 November 2013|work=birminghampost|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> He has also said, "My mum doesn't fit into any category, she's a black South African woman who's half Jewish."<ref name="mum">{{cite news|last1=Hook, Chris|first1=Horan, Patrick|title=Trevor Noah has Australia laughing|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/arts/trevor-noah-has-australia-laughing/story-fni0fcgk-1227096241477|accessdate=11 April 2015|work=[[Herald Sun|The Herald Sun]]|date=20 October 2014}}</ref> His parents' relationship was illegal at the time of his birth due to [[apartheid]], and his mother was jailed and fined by the South African government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allthingscomedy.com/contents/1851/17-ep-55---interview-with-south-african-comedian-trevor-noah-podcast|title=Ep. 55 - interview with South African comedian Trevor Noah|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> His father later moved back to Switzerland and Noah was raised by his mother and maternal grandmother, Nomalizo Frances Noah.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trevor Noah’s tough upbringing in Soweto will help him: granny|url=http://www.thenewage.co.za/155558-1007-53-Trevor_Noahs_tough_upbringing_in_Soweto_will_help_himgranny|accessdate=11 April 2015|work=[[The New Age (South African newspaper)|The New Age]]|date=2 April 2015}}</ref> During his childhood, he attended church every Sunday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3023806/How-stepfather-new-Daily-host-Trevor-Noah-tried-hunt-kill-shooting-mother-leaving-dead-South-African-slum-comedian-raised.html|title=Daily Show host Trevor Noah's stepfather tried to hunt and kill him|work=Mail Online}}</ref> 

He has two younger half-brothers by his mother's husband, Ngisaveni Shingange, whom she later divorced. In 2009, after she became engaged to another man,<ref name="citypress">{{cite news|title=Trevor Noah’s hell at home|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/entertainment/trevor-noahs-hell-at-home-20120303/|accessdate=11 April 2015|work=[[City Press (South Africa)|City Press]]|date=3 March 2012}}</ref> Shingange shot her in the back and face; he was unable to continue shooting as the gun jammed. He later threatened to kill Trevor Noah.<ref name="channel24">{{cite news|last1=Sidimba|first1=Loyiso|title=Trevor Noah 'fled' to Hollywood|url=http://www.channel24.co.za/TopStories/Trevor-Noah-fled-to-Hollywood-20120311|accessdate=11 April 2015|work=Channel24.co.za|date=11 March 2011}}</ref><ref name="citypress"/> In 2011, Shingange was convicted of attempted murder. Noah stated that he hoped the attention surrounding the incident would help the domestic abuse problem in South Africa: “For years my mother reached out to police for help with domestic abuse, and nothing was ever done. This is the norm in South Africa. Dockets went missing and cases never went to court.”<ref name="channel24"/> In 2012, Shingange was sentenced to only three years of "correctional supervision" for the attempted murder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Threats or No-ah threats, the tour is on|url=http://www.citypress.co.za/entertainment/threats-or-no-ah-threats-the-tour-is-on-20120804/|accessdate=11 April 2015|work=[[City Press (South Africa)|City Press]]|date=4 August 2012}}</ref>

His [[mixed-race]] heritage, his experiences growing up in a [[Soweto]] township, and his observations about race and ethnicity are leading themes in his comedy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Why mixed-race comic was 'born a crime' |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/13/showbiz/trevor-noah-comedy/index.html |accessdate=12 October 2013 |publisher=[[CNN]]  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Trevor Noah interview – Comedy interviews |work=Time Out London |url=http://www.timeout.com/london/comedy/trevor-noah-interview |accessdate=12 October 2013  }}</ref>

==Career==
Noah had a starring role on the South African [[soap opera]] ''[[Isidingo]]'' in 2002 when he was 18. He then began hosting his own radio show "Noah's Ark" on Gauteng's leading youth radio station, [[YFM]]. Noah then went on to host an educational program, "Run The Adventure" from 2004–06 on [[SABC 2]]. In 2007 he hosted ''The Real Goboza'', a gossip show on [[SABC 1]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvsa.co.za/actorprofile.asp?actorID=7105 |title=Trevor Noah - Actor Profile |publisher=Tvsa.co.za  |accessdate=4 November 2012 }}</ref> and ''Siyadlala'', a sports show which also aired on the SABC. In 2008 Noah co-hosted alongside Pabi Moloi on ''The Amazing Date'' (a dating game-show) and was a ''[[Strictly Come Dancing (South African TV series)|Strictly Come Dancing]]'' contestant in season 4. In 2009 he hosted the 3rd Annual South Africa Film and Television Awards (SAFTAs) and co-hosted alongside Eugene Khoza on ''The Axe Sweet Life'', a reality competition series. In 2010 Noah hosted the 16th annual ''[[South African Music Awards]]'' and also hosted ''Tonight with Trevor Noah'' on [[MNet]] (in the second season it moved to [[DStv]]'s Mzansi Magic Channel).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://beta.mnet.co.za/fanclub/?clubId=1744 |title=Tonight with Trevor Noah |publisher=Beta.mnet.co.za |date=1 April 2007 |accessdate=4 November 2012 }}</ref> In 2010, Noah also became a spokesperson and [[consumer protection]] agent for [[Cell C]], South Africa's third largest cellular provider.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cellc.co.za/tell-trevor/topic |title=Tell Trevor — Cell C South Africa |publisher=Cellc.co.za |date= |accessdate=4 November 2012 }}</ref>

Noah dropped his radio show and acting to focus on [[comedy]], and has performed with South African comedians such as [[David Kau]], [[Kagiso Lediga]], [[Riaad Moosa]], [[Darren Simpson]], [[Marc Lottering]], [[Barry Hilton]] and [[Nik Rabinowitz]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bafunnybafunny.com |title=Bafunny Bafunny official website |publisher= |date= |accessdate=4 November 2012}}</ref> international comedians such as [[Paul Rodriguez]], [[Carl Barron]], [[Dan Ilic]] and [[Paul Zerdin]], and as the opening act for [[Gabriel Iglesias]] in November 2007 and Canadian comedian [[Russell Peters]] on his South African tour.

Noah has performed all over South Africa in "The Blacks Only Comedy Show", the "Heavyweight Comedy Jam", the "Vodacom Campus Comedy Tour", the "Cape Town International Comedy Festival", the "Jozi Comedy Festival", and "Bafunny Bafunny" (2010).<ref>{{cite web |title=Bafunny, Bafunny |url=http://www.royalalberthall.com/tickets/bafunny-bafunny/default.aspx |publisher=[[Royal Albert Hall]]|accessdate=12 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Review: Bafunny, Bafunny |url=http://www.whatsonincapetown.com/post/review-bafunny-bafunny/ |accessdate=12 October 2013 }}</ref> His stand-up comedy specials in South Africa include ''The Daywalker'' (2009), ''Crazy Normal'' (2011), ''That's Racist'' (2012), and ''It's My Culture'' (2013).

He moved to the United States in 2011.<ref name="channel24"/> On 6 January 2012, Noah became the first South African stand-up comedian to appear on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' and on 17 May 2013, he became the first to appear on ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''.<ref name="Armstrong" /><ref>{{cite web |author=[[Jay Leno]] |url=http://www.nbc.com/the-tonight-show/episode-guide/2012-01-02/2012-01-06 |title=The Tonight Show with Jay Leno - Episode Guide |publisher=[[NBC]] |date= |accessdate=4 November 2012}}</ref> Noah was the subject of the 2012 documentary ''You Laugh But It's True''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youlaughbutitstrue.com|title=You Laugh But It's True|author=David Paul Meyer|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> The same year he starred in the one-man comedy show ''Trevor Noah: The Racist''<ref>{{cite web | title=''Trevor Noah: The Racist'' – review |url=http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2012/aug/16/trevor-noah-the-racist-review| accessdate = 12 October 2013 }}</ref> which was based on his similarly titled South African special ''That's Racist''. On 12 September, Noah was the Roastmaster in a [[Comedy Central Roast]] of South African [[Afrikaans]] singer [[Steve Hofmeyr]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.citypress.co.za/entertainment/war-of-words-erupts-after-hofmeyrs-roast-20120915/|title = War of words erupts after Hofmeyr’s roast|date = 15 September 2012|accessdate = 2 April 2015|website = City Press|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> 2013 he performed the comedy special ''Trevor Noah: African American,'' now available on DVD and digital platforms.<ref>{{cite web |title=Showtime : ''Trevor Noah: African American'' |url=http://www.sho.com/sho/comedy/titles/3379668/trevor-noah-african-american#/index | accessdate = 12 October 2013  }}</ref> On 11 October 2013 he was a guest on [[BBC Two]]'s comedy panel show ''[[QI]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=''QI'', Series K, Killers |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b03d3p60 |accessdate=12 October 2013}}</ref> On 29 November 2013 he was a panelist on [[Channel 4]] game show ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'',<ref>{{Twitter status|ChambersMgt|406437478627672064|.@jimmycarr is your hilarious host for 8 Out 10 Cats again tonight with international stand-up star .@Trevornoah as guest panelist. C4, 9pm!|Chamber's Management|29 November 2013|12 September 2014}}</ref> and appeared on Sean Lock's team in ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]'' on 12 September 2014.

===''The Daily Show''===
{{see|The Daily Show}}
In December 2014, Noah became a recurring contributor on ''[[The Daily Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://variety.com/2014/tv/news/the-daily-show-adds-comedians-hasan-minhaj-and-trevor-noah-1201326740/|title=‘The Daily Show’ Adds Comedians Hasan Minhaj and Trevor Noah|first=Shelli|last=Weinstein|work=Variety|date=10 October 2014|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> On 30 March 2015, [[Comedy Central]] announced that Noah will take over as host of ''The Daily Show'' when [[Jon Stewart]] leaves later in the year. His tenure will begin in either late 2015 or early 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|title=Trevor Noah to Succeed Jon Stewart on ‘The Daily Show’|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/31/arts/television/trevor-noah-to-succeed-jon-stewart-on-the-daily-show.html?src=twr&_r=1|accessdate=30 March 2015|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=30 March 2015}}</ref>

==Controversy==
Within hours of his announcement as Stewart's successor, several jokes were brought to light on his Twitter feed that some people deemed offensive to women, Jews, and Asians.<ref>{{cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|title=Trevor Noah, New ‘Daily Show’ Host, Comes Under Scrutiny for Tweets|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/01/arts/television/trevor-noah-new-daily-show-host-comes-under-scrutiny-for-tweets.html?smid=tw-nytmedia&seid=auto|accessdate=31 March 2015|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=31 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/641377/new-daily-show-host-trevor-noah-faces-backlash-over-controversial-tweets|title=New Daily Show Host Trevor Noah Faces Backlash Over Controversial Tweets|work=E! Online|date=31 March 2015}}</ref> Noah responded, "To reduce my views to a handful of jokes that didn't land is not a true reflection of my character, nor my evolution as a comedian," he tweeted.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/Trevornoah/status/583019964556152832 |title=Trevor Noah (Twitter) |last=Noah |first=Trevor |publisher=Twitter |accessdate=1 April 2015}}</ref> Comedy Central stood behind Noah, saying in a statement, "Like many comedians, Trevor Noah pushes boundaries; he is provocative and spares no one, himself included... To judge him or his comedy based on a handful of jokes is unfair. Trevor is a talented comedian with a bright future at Comedy Central."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/01/arts/television/trevor-noah-new-daily-show-host-comes-under-scrutiny-for-tweets.html?_r=0 |title=Comedy Central Stands Behind Trevor Noah, New ‘Daily Show’ Host, Amid Scrutiny |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=31 March 2015 |accessdate=1 April 2015 }}</ref> Mary Kluk, chairperson of the South African Jewish Board of Deputies, said that the jokes were not signs of anti-Jewish prejudice and that they were part of Noah's style of comedy. She stated, "The SAJBD wishes him all the success and wisdom that he will require in his new position, and is confident that he will do our country proud."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pillay|first1=Taschica|title=Trevor Noah's 'playful' jokes don't offend us - SA Jews|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/entertainment/celebrity/2015/04/06/trevor-noah-s-playful-jokes-don-t-offend-us---sa-jews|website=Times Live|accessdate=7 April 2015|date=6 April 2015}}</ref>

==Influences==
Noah has said of his comedic influences, "The kings are indisputable. [[Richard Pryor]]; [[Bill Cosby|Cosby]]; for me personally I didn't know of him before I started comedy but [[Eddie Murphy]] changed my view on the thing and I definitely look up to him as a comedic influence. [[Chris Rock]] in terms of the modern Black comedian and [[Dave Chappelle]]. Those are the guys that have laid the foundation and have moved the yard stick for all comedians, not just Black comedians."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essence.com/2013/06/18/trevor-noah-talks-being-south-african-comedian/ |title=New & Next: Meet South African Comedian Trevor Noah |publisher=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]] |date=14 June 2013 |accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> He also cited Jon Stewart as an influence, following his appointment to succeed Stewart as host of The Daily Show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/mar/30/trevor-noah-jon-stewart-daily-show-host |title=Trevor Noah to succeed Jon Stewart as host of The Daily Show |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |date=30 March 2015 |accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Noah is a [[Polyglotism|polyglot]]; he speaks several languages including [[English language|English]], [[German language|German]], [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]], [[Zulu language|isiZulu]], [[Sotho language|Sotho]], and [[Afrikaans]].<ref name="nytimes33114"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/whats-on/comedy-gigs/south-african-comedian-trevor-noah-6319931|title=South African comedian Trevor Noah to play Birmingham’s Glee Club|author=Roz Laws|date=22 November 2013|work=birminghampost}}</ref>

In 2015, it was reported he was dating South African physiotherapist  Dani Gabriel.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Findlay|first1=Stephanie|title=Trevor Noah's Daily Show gig a ‘moon landing’ for proud South Africans|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/world/2015/03/31/trevor-noahs-daily-show-gig-a-moon-landing-for-proud-south-africans.html|accessdate=11 April 2015|work=[[The Toronto Star]]|date=13 March 2015}}</ref>

Noah describes himself, like Jon Stewart, as a political [[Progressivism|progressive]].<ref>{{cite news|last=MOORE|first=FRAZIER|title=AP Exclusive: 'Daily Show' host Noah discusses his new gig |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2154409ae5014f73908218a9569dcce6/ap-exclusive-daily-show-host-noah-discusses-his-new-gig|accessdate=31 March 2015|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=31 March 2015}}</ref>

